\section*{Stratified sampling.}

This is a method of obtaining a sample from a population when distinct groups (strata) of a population can be identified. The principle of this sampling is to divide a population into different groups called strata such that each element of the population belongs to one and only stratum.

The population divided into groups should be in such a way that units within each group are as similar as possible. The groups should be homogeneous.

The composition of groups can be for instance different tribes, religions, gender, socio-economic groups, occupation, age, income groups etc.

The chosen variables should be one that result in internally homogeneous stratum, then within each stratum, random sampling is applied using either simple or systematic random method to choose the sample.

Stratified sampling can be proportional or non-proportional. In proportional sampling the participants are chosen in proportion to the number in each group. Non-proportional occurs when the response weight of the sub-group is not a factor.

